WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.735 --> 00:00:01.803
Narrator: What we're
going to do in this video

00:00:01.803 --> 00:00:05.536
is dig a little bit
deeper into labor markets.

00:00:05.536 --> 00:00:08.679
It's really not going to be
any fundamentally new concepts.

00:00:08.679 --> 00:00:11.206
We're really just going
to reapply concepts

00:00:11.206 --> 00:00:12.799
that we've already seen before and

00:00:12.799 --> 00:00:14.473
maybe use slightly different words,

00:00:14.473 --> 00:00:17.139
but the reason why labor is interesting

00:00:17.139 --> 00:00:19.724
is labor is one of the
factors of production.

00:00:19.724 --> 00:00:21.522
It's one of the inputs you need for firms

00:00:21.522 --> 00:00:23.821
to produce whatever they do produce.

00:00:24.129 --> 00:00:26.599
Unlike in most markets,

00:00:26.599 --> 00:00:28.270
if we're talking about
the computer markets,

00:00:28.270 --> 00:00:29.205
let me write over here.

00:00:29.205 --> 00:00:33.938
In the computer market, the demand

00:00:33.938 --> 00:00:36.023
is coming from individuals.

00:00:36.608 --> 00:00:39.083
It's coming from, I'll just
call it, individual people

00:00:39.083 --> 00:00:42.212
while the supply is coming from firms,

00:00:42.212 --> 00:00:43.886
is coming from firms.

00:00:44.210 --> 00:00:46.470
In the labor market it's
the other way around.

00:00:47.100 --> 00:00:50.669
In the labor market the demand is coming

00:00:50.669 --> 00:00:53.465
from firms, these are the
people who need labor,

00:00:53.465 --> 00:00:56.500
who are hiring the labor,
so this is coming from firms

00:00:56.500 --> 00:00:59.838
and the supply is coming
from individual people.

00:01:00.208 --> 00:01:04.682
So, it's coming from individual people.

00:01:05.282 --> 00:01:07.059
What's interesting about that is

00:01:07.059 --> 00:01:09.203
because the demand is coming from firms,

00:01:09.203 --> 00:01:12.103
in the past, when the supply
was coming from firms,

00:01:12.103 --> 00:01:13.842
we could look at a firms cost structure

00:01:13.842 --> 00:01:16.602
and we could come up with
a supply curve from that.

00:01:16.602 --> 00:01:18.672
Now that the demand is coming from firms,

00:01:18.672 --> 00:01:21.603
we can look at a firms, essentially
their revenue structure,

00:01:21.603 --> 00:01:23.338
how much incremental revenue do they get

00:01:23.338 --> 00:01:25.608
per extra employee and we could actually

00:01:25.608 --> 00:01:28.999
generate a demand curve,
their marginal benefit curve,

00:01:28.999 --> 00:01:31.278
by looking at their business
a little bit closer.

00:01:31.417 --> 00:01:33.747
That's essentially what we're
going to be doing in this video.

00:01:33.747 --> 00:01:35.532
These aren't any fundamentally new ideas,

00:01:35.532 --> 00:01:37.469
we just applying them in
a slightly different way

00:01:37.469 --> 00:01:39.347
and we'll use slightly different words.

00:01:39.747 --> 00:01:42.274
Now, let's assume, for
the sake of this video

00:01:42.274 --> 00:01:45.387
that I run a car wash, a car wash.

00:01:45.741 --> 00:01:47.543
It is a competitive car wash.

00:01:47.543 --> 00:01:50.020
It is a competitive car wash.

00:01:50.159 --> 00:01:52.209
I have to be a price taker.

00:01:52.209 --> 00:01:53.803
I do not have a monopoly, or an oligopoly.

00:01:53.803 --> 00:01:55.590
I'm not even a monopolistic competitor.

00:01:55.590 --> 00:01:57.425
There are many car washes in this city.

00:01:57.425 --> 00:02:00.408
We are undifferentiated. We are
all offering the same service.

00:02:00.408 --> 00:02:02.335
So, I'm going to be a price taker.

00:02:02.335 --> 00:02:04.914
Let's say the equilibrium
price in this market

00:02:04.914 --> 00:02:09.186
for competitive car
washes is $5 per car wash,

00:02:09.494 --> 00:02:11.863
$5 per car wash.

00:02:12.248 --> 00:02:14.471
Just as a little bit of
review, that also means,

00:02:14.471 --> 00:02:15.825
remember, this is a competitive firm,

00:02:15.825 --> 00:02:16.607
not a monopoly,

00:02:16.607 --> 00:02:21.336
that my marginal revenue is equal
to a constant $5 per car wash.

00:02:21.336 --> 00:02:24.005
If I do 1 car wash I'll
get $5, 2 car washes, $10

00:02:24.005 --> 00:02:26.335
3 car washes, $15.

00:02:26.335 --> 00:02:29.098
In a monopoly, the marginal
revenue would change.

00:02:29.098 --> 00:02:32.249
Let's think about how
much benefit I would get

00:02:32.249 --> 00:02:34.158
from each incremental employee.

00:02:34.943 --> 00:02:38.272
First, I'll do a ...
let's make this column

00:02:38.272 --> 00:02:41.125
right over here, let's
take this L for labor.

00:02:41.125 --> 00:02:43.403
This is going to be the quantity of labor.

00:02:43.403 --> 00:02:45.507
I'm going to think what
I hire, what zero people,

00:02:45.507 --> 00:02:50.598
1, 2, 3, 4, or 5 people.

00:02:51.598 --> 00:02:55.832
Let's think about how
much that we can produce

00:02:55.832 --> 00:02:58.340
when I hire these amounts of people.

00:02:58.340 --> 00:03:02.004
I'll call that total
product, or we could call it

00:03:02.004 --> 00:03:04.037
total product of labor.

00:03:04.037 --> 00:03:06.404
It's essentially saying,
how many cars can I wash?

00:03:06.404 --> 00:03:08.333
This is going to be car washes per hour,

00:03:09.086 --> 00:03:14.540
so cars washed per hour.

00:03:15.602 --> 00:03:17.418
How many cars can I wash
per hour with a different

00:03:17.418 --> 00:03:18.838
number of people here?

00:03:18.838 --> 00:03:21.504
Well, if I have zero people,
I'm going to wash zero cars.

00:03:21.504 --> 00:03:23.505
Let's say that I find if I have one person

00:03:23.505 --> 00:03:27.756
that person can wash 5 cars
per hour by him or herself.

00:03:27.756 --> 00:03:30.335
Two people can wash 9 cars together.

00:03:30.335 --> 00:03:32.243
Three people can do 12 cars.

00:03:32.243 --> 00:03:34.206
Four people can do 14

00:03:34.206 --> 00:03:38.819
and 5 people can do 15 cars together.

00:03:38.819 --> 00:03:39.844
We can plot this.

00:03:39.844 --> 00:03:41.497
Let's actually plot this on a graph

00:03:41.497 --> 00:03:43.081
just to see what's going on.

00:03:43.081 --> 00:03:44.542
It always helps to visualize things,

00:03:45.203 --> 00:03:48.881
so that is going to be our total product.

00:03:50.020 --> 00:03:52.119
That is going to be our total product

00:03:52.119 --> 00:03:56.136
and this is going to be
our quantity of labor.

00:03:56.136 --> 00:04:03.866
The quantity of labor we can
have 1, 2, 3, 4, or 5 people

00:04:03.866 --> 00:04:05.849
and this is actually zero
people right over here

00:04:05.849 --> 00:04:08.334
and my total product goes
all the way up to 15.

00:04:08.334 --> 00:04:11.603
Let's say that this is
15, this would be 10

00:04:11.603 --> 00:04:12.992
and this would be 5,

00:04:12.992 --> 00:04:15.331
5, 10 and 15.

00:04:15.670 --> 00:04:17.872
So we can plot these
points right over here.

00:04:17.872 --> 00:04:19.736
What is the total product?

00:04:19.736 --> 00:04:21.402
Well, this is zero/zero.

00:04:21.402 --> 00:04:24.438
Zero people, I'm not
washing any cars per hour.

00:04:24.808 --> 00:04:26.777
Total product is in cars washed per hour.

00:04:27.008 --> 00:04:32.068
If I have 1 person, I
can wash 5 cars per hour.

00:04:32.652 --> 00:04:36.739
If I have 2 people I can
wash 9 cars per hour,

00:04:36.739 --> 00:04:39.544
2 people I can wash 9 cars per hour,

00:04:39.544 --> 00:04:43.007
3 people, I can was 12 cars per hour,

00:04:43.007 --> 00:04:46.915
3 people I can wash 12 cars,
that's about right there.

00:04:46.915 --> 00:04:50.011
Four people, I can wash 14 cars per hour,

00:04:50.395 --> 00:04:53.280
4 people, 14 is right about there

00:04:53.280 --> 00:04:56.334
and then finally I will do this ...

00:04:56.334 --> 00:04:58.208
well let's see. I'm already
using a lot of my colors.

00:04:58.208 --> 00:04:59.005
Let's see, pink.

00:04:59.005 --> 00:05:01.608
Five people, I can wash 15 cars per hour,

00:05:01.608 --> 00:05:04.667
5 people I could wash 15 cars per hour.

00:05:05.421 --> 00:05:09.135
So, total product is a
function of quantity of labor

00:05:09.135 --> 00:05:11.000
it will look like a curve that
looks something like this.

00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:12.003
I could just connect the dots

00:05:12.003 --> 00:05:13.606
or I could make it look
a little bit more curvy,

00:05:14.375 --> 00:05:18.789
so it's going to look something like that.

00:05:19.682 --> 00:05:21.267
One way that we should think about it,

00:05:21.267 --> 00:05:23.319
as you'll see in economics
when you always want

00:05:23.319 --> 00:05:24.673
to think about how much
you want to produce

00:05:24.673 --> 00:05:26.002
or how much you want to hire,

00:05:26.002 --> 00:05:26.843
you always want to think about

00:05:26.843 --> 00:05:29.867
how much benefit are you getting
for that incremental thing

00:05:29.867 --> 00:05:31.501
when you're thinking
about your cost structure.

00:05:31.501 --> 00:05:33.335
How much cost for that incremental unit?

00:05:33.335 --> 00:05:35.535
When you're thinking about your benefits

00:05:35.535 --> 00:05:36.580
or your demand, you're thinking,

00:05:36.580 --> 00:05:38.003
how much benefit am I getting from

00:05:38.003 --> 00:05:39.180
that incremental unit?

00:05:39.518 --> 00:05:42.473
Let's view this as the marginal ...

00:05:42.473 --> 00:05:45.748
Let's write marginal product, MP.

00:05:45.748 --> 00:05:47.937
Sometimes in some economics text books

00:05:47.937 --> 00:05:49.868
I've seen this referred to as MPL,

00:05:49.868 --> 00:05:51.504
marginal product of labor.

00:05:51.504 --> 00:05:52.536
Actually, I'll just write the L there

00:05:52.536 --> 00:05:53.211
to make this clear.

00:05:53.211 --> 00:05:55.942
This is the marginal product of labor.

00:05:55.942 --> 00:05:59.418
So, when we go from
zero people to 1 person,

00:05:59.418 --> 00:06:02.136
on average between those
2 points over there,

00:06:02.136 --> 00:06:04.751
we're able to ... our delta, our change.

00:06:04.751 --> 00:06:08.335
Delta is just the Greek
letter that symbolizes change.

00:06:08.781 --> 00:06:10.674
Our change in total product is 5.

00:06:10.828 --> 00:06:14.936
We can view that as the
average marginal product,

00:06:14.936 --> 00:06:17.807
or you can kind of view
that as marginal product

00:06:17.807 --> 00:06:19.422
halfway between these or
you could view that as

00:06:19.422 --> 00:06:21.845
the average marginal product between

00:06:21.845 --> 00:06:23.329
those two points right over there.

00:06:23.329 --> 00:06:24.469
That's why I wrote it in a row.

00:06:24.469 --> 00:06:26.543
That it is in between these two points.

00:06:26.543 --> 00:06:29.472
It's taking us from zero to 1.

00:06:29.472 --> 00:06:32.468
Actually, let me plot
these while I calculate

00:06:32.468 --> 00:06:33.667
what they are.

00:06:33.667 --> 00:06:38.450
So, I'll draw this one
a little bit more flat,

00:06:38.450 --> 00:06:41.940
