scroll down a little bit.

00:06:41.940 --> 00:06:46.622
So, in this axis I'm going to
do marginal product of labor

00:06:46.622 --> 00:06:48.197
and then on this axis I'm going to have

00:06:48.197 --> 00:06:49.551
the quantity of labor.

00:06:49.551 --> 00:06:57.406
This is 1, this is 2, this
is 3, 4 people and 5 people.

00:06:57.406 --> 00:06:59.439
So, this point right over here,

00:06:59.439 --> 00:07:01.689
this point right over here, that's the

00:07:01.689 --> 00:07:03.600
marginal product of labor, halfway.

00:07:03.600 --> 00:07:05.431
You could view this as a slope halfway

00:07:05.431 --> 00:07:07.546
between zero and 1 or you could view this

00:07:07.546 --> 00:07:10.004
as the average slope from zero to 1.

00:07:10.004 --> 00:07:11.630
So, I'll plot it right over here.

00:07:11.630 --> 00:07:14.373
I'll view it and actually I
haven't labeled these axis.

00:07:14.373 --> 00:07:19.686
This is, let's call this 5, 4, 3, 2, 1.

00:07:20.163 --> 00:07:22.857
So, halfway between zero and 1

00:07:22.857 --> 00:07:26.056
my marginal product of labor is 5,

00:07:26.056 --> 00:07:27.736
right over there.

00:07:27.736 --> 00:07:32.085
Then halfway between 1 and 2,

00:07:32.085 --> 00:07:35.212
my marginal product of labor,
I go from 5 cars washed

00:07:35.212 --> 00:07:38.870
per hour to 9, so my marginal
product of labor is 4.

00:07:38.870 --> 00:07:43.069
So, between 1 and 2 my
marginal product of labor is 4

00:07:43.699 --> 00:07:48.264
and then between 2 and 3,

00:07:48.264 --> 00:07:49.644
my marginal product of labor,

00:07:49.644 --> 00:07:53.006
I go from 9 car washes,
cars washed per hour to 12.

00:07:53.006 --> 00:07:55.322
So, I have 3 incremental cars washed

00:07:55.322 --> 00:07:57.212
by adding that third person,

00:07:57.212 --> 00:07:58.986
so the average that you could view that

00:07:58.986 --> 00:08:02.122
as the slope right over
there is going to be 3.

00:08:02.122 --> 00:08:04.661
So, the slope right over
there is going to be 3.

00:08:05.077 --> 00:08:07.721
I didn't make this completely to scale

00:08:07.721 --> 00:08:10.071
and then, these are a
little bit more bunched up

00:08:10.071 --> 00:08:12.338
down here, but let's just keep going.

00:08:12.338 --> 00:08:14.869
Then from going from 3 to 4,

00:08:14.869 --> 00:08:16.705
the marginal product of labor,

00:08:16.705 --> 00:08:19.044
I'll go from 12 cars washed to 14,

00:08:19.044 --> 00:08:22.378
so I get 2 extra cars washed
by adding that fourth person,

00:08:22.378 --> 00:08:25.871
so between 3 and 4 I get
an incremental, on average,

00:08:25.871 --> 00:08:29.803
2 cars for that extra person

00:08:29.803 --> 00:08:34.003
and then finally between 4
and 5, I get one extra car.

00:08:34.003 --> 00:08:37.069
So, between 4 and 5 I
get exactly 1 extra car.

00:08:37.069 --> 00:08:40.007
I'm going to get, it looks a
